UK_FARMING = """UK CROP CALENDAR AND AGRONOMY

Brassicas (cabbage, cauliflower, calabrese, sprouting broccoli, Brussels sprouts, kale, swede, turnip): sow spring to midsummer depending on type, usually raised in modules and transplanted. Spring cabbage sown Jul to Aug and overwintered; summer cabbage sown Feb to Apr; winter cabbage and savoys sown Apr to May. Brussels sprouts sown Mar to Apr for a long season standing into winter. Prefer firm, fertile, limed soil at pH 6.5 to 7.5 to suppress clubroot. Main threats are clubroot, cabbage root fly (use collars), caterpillars of cabbage white (net the crop), mealy cabbage aphid and flea beetle.

Roots. Carrots sow Mar to Jul directly, need a soil temperature above about 7C to germinate, sow thinly to reduce carrot root fly and use fleece or barriers. Parsnips sow Feb to Apr, slow to germinate, need fresh seed. Beetroot sow Apr to Jul. Radish is fast, sow little and often. Maincrop roots store over winter.

Alliums. Onions from sets Mar to Apr, or autumn sets planted Aug to Oct for an early crop. Garlic planted Oct to Nov so it gets a cold spell to form bulbs. Leeks sown Feb to Apr, transplanted, and harvested autumn through winter. Onion white rot and downy mildew are the main problems and rotation matters.

Legumes. Broad beans sown Nov for an early crop or Feb to Apr in spring, watch chocolate spot and blackfly. Peas Mar to Jun in succession. Runner and French beans are frost tender, sow under cover Apr or outside late May to Jun once frost has passed.

Potatoes. Chit seed potatoes first, plant first earlies in Mar, second earlies Apr, maincrop Apr to May. Earth up to stop greening. First earlies lift from Jun, maincrop Sep to Oct. Potatoes are frost tender. Late blight (Phytophthora infestans) is the key risk in warm humid spells from Jul, use resistant varieties, watch blight warnings and destroy haulm if infected. Common scab is worse on high pH and dry soils, so potatoes tolerate a lower pH around 5.0 to 6.0.

Salads. Lettuce, rocket, spinach and chard sown little and often spring to late summer, some overwinter under cover.

Cereals and combinable crops. Winter wheat is drilled Sep to Oct and harvested Aug the next year, giving the highest yields. Spring wheat and spring barley drilled Feb to Apr. Winter barley drilled early autumn and harvested a little before wheat. Oats spring or winter sown. Oilseed rape drilled Aug to early Sep and cut Jul to Aug, with cabbage stem flea beetle a major establishment pest and pollen beetle at flowering. Field beans and peas are useful break crops that fix nitrogen. Forage maize drilled late Apr to May once soil is above about 8 to 10C and cut for silage Sep to Oct. Sugar beet in the east, drilled spring, lifted autumn to winter.

Grass and forage. Grass grows Apr to Oct in the UK. First cut silage is usually mid May to early Jun at early heading for quality, hay is made in settled weather Jun to Jul, haylage sits between the two. Reseed leys in spring or Aug to Sep with perennial ryegrass, often with white clover which fixes nitrogen. Forage brassicas such as kale, stubble turnips, forage rape and swede are grown to graze livestock through autumn and winter. Fodder beet is a high energy winter feed.

SOIL, pH AND SEASONS

Most crops want pH 6.0 to 7.0. Brassicas prefer 6.5 to 7.5, potatoes tolerate more acid, blueberries need acid soil. Correct low pH with lime. Soils range from free draining sand and chalk to heavy water holding clay, with loam the ideal. Heavy clay is slow to warm and work in spring. Organic matter from farmyard manure, compost and cover crops improves structure, water holding and biology. The UK last frost is typically Apr to May and first frost Oct to Nov, earlier and harder in the north and inland, milder near the coast and in the south west. Growing degree days accumulate faster in a warm spell.

CROP ROTATION

Rotate to break pest and disease cycles and balance nutrients. A simple vegetable rotation moves ground through legumes, then brassicas, then roots, then potatoes and alliums. The classic Norfolk four course was wheat, turnips, barley then clover. Never grow brassicas on the same ground repeatedly because of clubroot, nor potatoes because of eelworm and blight, nor onions because of white rot.

PESTS AND DISEASES

Clubroot in brassicas, manage with lime, long rotation and resistant varieties. Late blight in potatoes and tomatoes in warm humid weather. Carrot root fly, use barriers, fleece and careful timing. Cabbage white caterpillars, cabbage root fly, flea beetle, aphids which also spread viruses, slugs and snails in wet conditions, wireworm and leatherjackets in ground out of grass, pea moth, and cabbage stem flea beetle and pollen beetle in oilseed rape. In cereals the main diseases are septoria in wheat, yellow and brown rust, take all, fusarium ear blight, and barley yellow dwarf virus spread by aphids. Integrated control combines resistant varieties, rotation, hygiene, timing, encouraging natural predators and only then targeted treatment.

SHEEP

Common UK breeds. Hill and upland breeds such as Scottish Blackface, Swaledale, Herdwick and Welsh Mountain are hardy. Lowland and terminal sire breeds such as Suffolk, Texel and Charollais give fast growing lambs. Maternal and crossing types such as the Mule, Lleyn and Romney are prolific and good mothers.

The sheep year. Tupping or mating is usually Oct to Nov. Gestation is about 147 days, roughly five months, so lambing falls Feb to Apr, earlier for housed flocks. Ewes are scanned in mid pregnancy to count lambs and feed accordingly. Lambs are weaned around 12 to 16 weeks. Good colostrum in the first hours is vital. Watch for hypothermia, watery mouth, joint ill and mismothering at lambing.

Grazing and fencing. Sheep are set stocked or rotationally grazed and are famous escapers, so containment needs proper stock fencing, typically sheep netting sometimes called C8 or 80 netting, or electric netting. If sheep are getting into a crop the answer is almost always better fencing rather than deterrents. Brassica crops like stubble turnips, kale and forage rape are often grown on purpose to graze sheep, but introduce them gradually over a week or two to let the rumen adjust, do not let brassicas make up the whole diet, and always offer run back to grass, water and a fibre source.

Health. Lameness is commonly footrot or scald caused by Dichelobacter, managed with prompt treatment, foot bathing in zinc sulphate and not over trimming. Gut worms are controlled with grazing management and strategic wormers guided by faecal egg counts to slow resistance. Liver fluke is a risk on wet pasture where the mud snail lives, mainly autumn and winter. Sheep scab is a mite that causes intense itching and wool loss and must be treated. Blowfly strike in warm summer months is prevented by dagging, shearing, and preventive pour ons. Clostridial diseases and pasteurella are prevented by vaccinating with a standard multi way vaccine and boosting ewes before lambing to protect lambs through colostrum.

CATTLE

Beef and dairy. Cows calve after about nine months. Grazed grass and grass or maize silage are the main feeds. Bovine TB is a major regulated disease with regular testing in higher risk areas. Other key issues are BVD, which schemes aim to eradicate, mastitis and lameness such as digital dermatitis in dairy, and youngstock pneumonia. Cattle need passports and movements are recorded.

POULTRY

Laying hens and broilers. Provide housing, clean water, feed and protection from predators. Avian influenza can trigger mandatory housing orders that keep birds inside. Red mite is a persistent pest of hen houses.

SOIL FERTILITY AND NUTRIENTS

Crops need nitrogen, phosphate and potash plus lime to hold pH and trace elements. Farmyard manure and slurry recycle nutrients and build organic matter. The RB209 nutrient guide sets sensible application rates. In Nitrate Vulnerable Zones there are legal limits and closed periods when nitrogen rich manures and fertilisers cannot be spread, mainly through autumn and winter, to protect water. Soil test every few years and lime to keep pH in range.

UK FARM SUPPORT AND ASSURANCE

In England the old Basic Payment Scheme has been phased out and replaced by Environmental Land Management, which includes the Sustainable Farming Incentive, Countryside Stewardship and Landscape Recovery, paying for actions like cover crops, hedgerows, buffer strips and healthy soils. Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland run their own schemes. Red Tractor is the main farm assurance standard. Livestock keepers need a holding number, must tag and record animals, sheep use electronic tags, and movements are reported. These rules change over time so treat specifics as a guide and check the current official position.

CLIMATE

The UK has a temperate maritime climate, mild and wet, with the east drier and the west and north wetter. This shapes what grows where and why grass and livestock dominate the wetter uplands while combinable crops favour the drier east."""
